3fb0e582-e735-4174-bf50-2d754d14accb.11732343-e795-4bab-9ef1-eb883420d053.description=
Iterates through a list of values. Modifying the value of the list and delimiter inputs during iteration is not generally supported.

Inputs\:
list - The list to iterate through.
separator - A delimiter that separates elements in the list.

Returns\:
The current element of the list, if the response is has more

Responses\:
has more - Another value was in the list, and has been returned.
has no more - The iterator has gone fully through the list. This response will only be returned once per iteration through the list, a subsequent call to the Iterator will restart the Iteration through the list.
failure - failed to process the list.

Note\: Where the iterator is in the list is tracked by each step's unique id. Therefore you can iterate on the same list from multiple steps simultaneously.

WARNING\: Any step that will use the results of this Iterator operation will, by default, attempt to assign that step's inputs from a flow variable. If this is left checked, then the first element of the iterator will be used for every cycle of iteration.
3fb0e582-e735-4174-bf50-2d754d14accb.11b92adf-473b-4790-bf40-8438dd745cc9.prompt=Password\: 3fb0e582-e735-4174-bf50-2d754d14accb.32ea05c0-1469-415f-b3dc-0e175e21ec90.description=
Useful Op to keep a running results.
Takes a string input (resultText) and appends this to a global context key of "runningResults". As a result, the context key whose name is in the keyName input will be appended with the string from the input resultText.

Input Parameters\:
keyName - name of context key to append to
resultText - string input to append
delimiter - (leave blank for none) the delimiter to put between what is already in keyName before appending resultText

Responses\:
success - assigned the context variable

Returns\:
The the value of the context variable it appended to.

Context\:
runningResults

Scriptlet Example\:
currentResults \= scriptletContext.get("runningResults");

if (currentResults \=\= null) {
   currentResults \= resultText;
} else {
   currentResults +\= resultText;
}


scriptletContext.putGlobal("runningResults", currentResults);

3fb0e582-e735-4174-bf50-2d754d14accb.574f29c0-41ab-4954-be54-8edaac383fae.description=
Sends an smtp email
 
Input Parameters\:
hostname - hostname or ip address of smtp server
port - port smtp service is listening
from - from email address
to - email address(s) or recipients
subject - email subject
body - body of the email
htmlEmail - true or false, whether the email should be sent supporting html rich email.
readReceipt - true or false, whether or not to request a read receipt
attachments - comma separated list of files to attach (must be full path)
username - if SMTP authentication is needed, the username to send
password - the password to use
characterSet - the character set encoding for the entire email which includes subject, body, attached file name and the attached file. Default value is UTF-8
contentTransferEncoding - the content transfer encoding scheme (such as 7bit, 8bit, base64, quoted-printable etc) for the entire email which includes subject, body, attached file name and the attached file. Default value is - quoted-printable or Q Encoding.
 
 Responses\:
 success - successfully sent the email
 failure - failed to send the email

Note\:
For special characters (East Asian, right-to-left languages, etc.) you must install the support files on your local machine.
	For doing this on Windows go to Control Panel -> Regional and Language Options -> Language and check the options at Supplemental language support.

3fb0e582-e735-4174-bf50-2d754d14accb.6bdbcf8e-88a1-4dbb-8eab-2482213d78e9.description=
Runs a SQL command against an Oracle database, using the information available in the tnsnames.ora file.   
Does not return any results (only whether the command was executed)

Input Parameters\:
TNSPath - The path to the parent folder of the TNS file which contains the DB connecting info(the name of the DB server, the port used for connecting to the DB server, the database name)
TNSEntry - the entry name from the tnsnames.ora file which contains the connecting information
Username - username to connect as
Password - password
Command - the command to execute

Responses\:
more items - the command was executed successfully
failure - the command could not be executed

Extra Results\:
updateCount - the update count of the command executed

NOTE\: 
This op supports only Oracle. The tnsnames.ora file should correctly configured on the RAS machine.

ORACLE NOTE\:
It is possible to run PL/SQL procedures using this operation. The examples below present the syntax to be used for having the same effect as the following PL/SQL script\:
BEGIN
  send_message(addressee\=>'b@hp.com',sender\=>'pas@hp.com',subject\=>'Test',message\=>'Test');
END;

Example 1\: BEGIN send_message(addressee\=>'b@hp.com',sender\=>'pas@hp.com',subject\=>'Test',message\=>'Test');END;

Example 2\: BEGIN send_message('b@hp.com','pas@hp.com','Test','Test');END;

Example 3\: {CALL send_message(addressee\=>'b@hp.com',sender\=>'pas@hp.com',subject\=>'Test',message\=>'Test')}

Example 4\: {CALL send_message('b@hp.com','pas@hp.com','Test','Test')}
3fb0e582-e735-4174-bf50-2d754d14accb.6f5b163c-eb84-4bac-b958-26d60ec10e44.description=Search for VMWare objects and their properties from a root object (if any). Retrieve each object's properties one at a time from an initial search query ala SQL Query operation. Inputs\: host - VMWare host hostname or IP user - VMWare username password - VMWare user's password port - Port to connect on protocol - Connection protocol (http or https) closeSession - Close the internally kept VMWare Infrastructure API session at completion of operation? propsType - VMWare properties type (Task, Datacenter, VirtualMachine, etc.) to filter on propsPathset - Property filter's pathset propsRootObjType - VMWare object type (eg. VirtualMachine, HostSystem, ComputeResource,ResourcePool,Alarm) propsRootObj - VMWare object ID Responses\: success - The operation completed successfully. failure - Something went wrong. no more - there are no more results to retrieve. Returns\: numberOfResults - Number of results from the query remaining to be retrieved returnResult - Query result item or operation result 3fb0e582-e735-4174-bf50-2d754d14accb.70874188-5e2b-41bc-bdf9-feaf11648071.description=

3fb0e582-e735-4174-bf50-2d754d14accb.72f5ed5b-5e38-4831-969f-fb974239ca05.description=
Compares two strings, returning a true response if and only if they contain the same sequence of characters. A null string is considered to be equal to an empty string.

Inputs\:
string1 - The first string.
string2 - The second string.
ignoreCase - If set to 'true', then the comparison ignores case considerations. The two strings are considered equal ignoring case if they are of the same length and corresponding characters in the two strings are equal ignoring case. If set to any value other than 'true', then the strings must match exactly to be considered equal.

responses\:
true - If the two strings are equal
false - If the two strings are not equal

Check to see if the value stored in a specified flow variable, denoted by key, is null.

Inputs\:
keyName - The key to check, i.e. the name of the flow variable.

Returns\: 
The value in the specified key, i.e. flow variable.

Responses\:
isNull - If the key is a null pointer, i.e. the flow variable doesn't have an assigned value.
notNull - If some value is stored in the key, i.e the flow variable has a value assigned.

3fb0e582-e735-4174-bf50-2d754d14accb.fc08449e-b543-49a4-8c36-466d695d9186.description=
Runs a SQL query against an Oracle database, using the information available in the tnsnames.ora file.  
The first row is returned on the first run of the operation.
Subsequent calls with the same information will return the other rows.

Inputs\:
TNSPath - The path to the parent folder of the TNS file which contains the DB connecting info(the name of the DB server, the port used for connecting to the DB server, the database name).
TNSEntry - The entry name from the tnsnames.ora file which contains the connecting information.
Username - The username used for connecting to the database.
Password - The password used for connecting to the database.
Command - The command to execute.
Delimiter - Delimiter to use between columns in returnResult.
Key - Key to help keep multiple query results distinct.

Responses\:
more items - More rows are available for retrieval.
no more items - No more rows are available.
failure - There was an error executing the command.

Extra Results\:
columnNames - The names of all the columns returned, separated by Delimiter.
rowsLeft - The number of rows remaining that match the query.

NOTE\: 
This op supports only Oracle. The tnsnames.ora file should be correctly configured on the RAS machine.

ORACLE NOTE\:
Only the "SELECT" statement can be executed using this operation. For statements that modify the database, use "TNS Names SQL Command".
